/orgs", "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/edaniszewski/repos", "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/edaniszewski/events{/privacy}", "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/edaniszewski/received_events", "type": "User", "site_admin": false}], "milestone": null, "comments": 2, "created_at": "2018-04-18T19:24:13Z", "updated_at": "2018-04-19T06:20:43Z", "closed_at": "2018-04-19T06:20:43Z", "author_association": "NONE", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "```\r\nIn Python, single-quoted strings and double-quoted strings are the same. \r\nThis PEP does not make a recommendation for this. Pick a rule and stick to it. \r\n**When a string contains single or double quote characters, however, use the \r\nother one to avoid backslashes in the string. It improves readability.**\r\n```\r\nhttps://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#string-quotes\r\n\r\nCurrently pylint-quotes wants you to religiously use one or the other and does not allow you to switch from mandated choice for strings that contain the mandated choice within them to avoid backslashes.\r\n\r\nTo be crystal clear I'd like to be able to have the following be true:\r\n\r\na = 'my standard style' # ok\r\nb = \"not my standard style\" # pylint warning\r\nc = \"this isn't a warning\" # ok\r\n\r\nWould this be hard to do?\r\n", "performed_via_github_app": null, "score": 1.0}, {"url": "https://api.github.com/repos/edaniszewski/pylint-quotes/issues/8", "repository_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/edaniszewski/pylint-quotes", "labels_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/edaniszewski/pylint-quotes/issues/8/labels{/name}", "comments_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/edaniszewski/pylint-quotes/issues/8/comments", "events_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/edaniszewski/pylint-quotes/issues/8/events", "html_url": "https://github.com/edaniszewski/pylint-quotes/issues/8", "id": 300997320, "node_id": "MDU6SXNzdWUzMDA5OTczMjA=", "number": 8, "title": "Wrong handling of `async def`", "user": {"logi